                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;The C++ Standard doesn&apos;t &quot;import&quot; the C Standard. It &lt;i&gt;references&lt;/i&gt; the C Standard. The C++ library introduction says &quot;The library also makes available the facilities of the Standard C Library&quot;. It does that by including headers of the C Standard library with appropriate changes, but not by &quot;importing&quot; it. The C++ Standard has an own set of rules that describes the reserved names. If a name reserved in C should be reserved in C++, that is the place to say this. But the C++ Standard doesn&apos;t say so. So i don&apos;t believe that things reserved in C are reserved in C++ - but i could well be wrong.&lt;/span&gt;

