                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@sbi According to the C and C++ standards, yes, semantically, global identifiers with leading underscores are reserved. They are syntactically valid identifiers though, and the compiler won&apos;t stop you from naming a function &lt;code&gt;_Foo&lt;/code&gt;, though by doing so you&apos;re relying on nonstandard implementation details and thus risk having your code broken by future versions of the language/standard library implementation/OS.&lt;/span&gt;

